INFO 11-14 22:11:34 [logger.py:43] Received request chatcmpl-0127080bca7a4d4c991370b959475a47: prompt: "<s>[INST] Hi, here's some system prompt: hi.For user 14, here are some other context: hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi hi.\n\nPlease respond to all 5 conversations above. Provide comprehensive answers for each conversation.\n\n--- Conversation 1 ---\nQuestion: 51 What type of database access is MOST APPROPRIATE for a researcher examining secular trends in\nPneumocystis jirovecii pneumonia?\na. File system access\nb. Live database, read-only\nc. Shadow (i.e. replica) only\nd. System administrator access\nAnswer: b. Live database, read-only.\n\nThis type of access allows the researcher to access the necessary data for their analysis without being able to make changes or modify the data in any way. It also ensures the integrity of the data and prevents accidental or intentional alteration. File system access and system administrator access would provide too much access and control, while shadow access only provides a replica of the data without the ability to interact with the original source.\n\n\n--- Conversation 2 ---\nQuestion: 52 A software tester is evaluating an application, but has no access to the source code. She designs tests\nbased on what the software is supposed to do, according to the project requirements. One characteristic\nof this type of testing is:\na. It is a form of static testing.\nb. It is composed of code reviews and structural assessment.\nc. Testers generally do not have to have technical knowledge of the relevant programming\nlanguages.\nd. Tests usually involve small code fragments, such as a module or a class.\nAnswer: The characteristic of the type of testing described in the scenario is:\nc. Testers generally do not have to have technical knowledge of the relevant programming languages.\n\nThis type of testing is called black box testing, where testers evaluate the software's functionality and behavior based on its input and output without knowledge of its internal workings. This type of testing focuses on the software's external behavior, and testers do not require knowledge of the programming language or the software's internal structure.\n\n\n--- Conversation 3 ---\nQuestion: 53 Although information retrieval primarily deals with unstructured data, queries often benefit from the use\nof supplementary information which accompanies documents, known as\na. Corpus\nb. Index\nc. Metadata\nd. Relevancy\nAnswer: c. Metadata\n\n\n--- Conversation 4 ---\nQuestion: 55 An implementer of Electronic Health Records requires using the New York Heart Association’s Classes of\nHeart Failure (shown below) to stratify patients. This is an example of a/an\nClass Patient Symptoms\n1 No limitation of physical\nactivity.\n2 Slight limitation of\nphysical activity.\n3 Marked limitation of\nphysical activity.\n4 Unable to carry on any\nphysical activity\nwithout discomfort\n\na. Controlled vocabulary\nb. Ontogeny\nc. Semantic encoding\nd. Taxonomy\nAnswer: Answer: d. Taxonomy.\n\nThe New York Heart Association's classes of heart failure is an example of a taxonomy, which is a hierarchical classification scheme used to organize and classify concepts or objects. In this case, the taxonomy is used to stratify heart failure patients based on their symptoms.\n\n\n--- Conversation 5 ---\nQuestion: 56 Certain users of a clinical information system are often provided with early or extra training. These\n“super-users”\na. Are responsible for maintaining passwords and access levels\nb. Attenuate security concerns\nc. May help train other users\nd. Set up interfaces with other clinical systems\nAnswer: c. May help train other users.\n\nSuper-users are typically experienced and highly skilled users of a clinical information system who receive extra training to assist with system implementation and to provide ongoing support to other users. They are not responsible for maintaining passwords and access levels or setting up interfaces with other clinical systems, although they may help to attenuate security concerns by monitoring user activity and reporting suspicious behavior to system administrators. [/INST]", params: SamplingParams(n=1, presence_penalty=0.0, frequency_penalty=0.0, repetition_penalty=1.0, temperature=0.0, top_p=1.0, top_k=0, min_p=0.0, seed=None, stop=[], stop_token_ids=[], bad_words=[], include_stop_str_in_output=False, ignore_eos=False, max_tokens=100, min_tokens=0, logprobs=None, prompt_logprobs=None, skip_special_tokens=True, spaces_between_special_tokens=True, truncate_prompt_tokens=None, guided_decoding=None, extra_args=None), prompt_token_ids: None, prompt_embeds shape: None, lora_request: None, prompt_adapter_request: None.
